'''Naobi no Kami''' (直毘神, also spelled なほびのかみ) is a deity in {{ill|Shinto|ja|神道|12=draft}}.

Naobi no Kami is believed to be a deity that purifies defilement ({{ill|Kegare|ja|穢れ|12=draft}}) and rectifies {{ill|Magatsuhi|ja|禍|12=draft}} (disasters or evils).<ref>[http://www.norinaga.jp/shoin/naobitama.html Naobi Tama - Original Text]</ref>

== Mythological Background ==
In the {{ill|Japanese mythology|ja|日本神話|12=draft}} narrative of the {{ill|kuniumi|lt=Birth of the Gods|ja|神産み|12=draft}}, after {{ill|Izanagi|ja|イザナギ|12=draft}} returned from {{ill|Yomi|ja|黄泉|12=draft}}, he performed {{ill|Misogi|ja|禊|12=draft}} (purification) to cleanse himself of Yomi's defilement. During this ritual, the impurities gave rise to {{ill|Magatsuhi no Kami|ja|禍津日神|12=draft}}. To counteract the calamities caused by Magatsuhi no Kami, Naobi no Kami was born. 

In the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft}}, following the emergence of Yaso-Magatsuhi no Kami and Ōmagatsuhi no Kami, three deities were born: {{ill|Kamunaobi no Kami|ja|神直毘神|12=draft}} (神直毘神), {{ill|Ōnaobi no Kami|ja|大直毘神|12=draft}} (大直毘神), and {{ill|Izunome|ja|伊豆能売|12=draft}}. In contrast, the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft}}, in the fifth section, sixth alternate writing, states that Kamunaobi no Kami and Ōnaobi no Kami emerged after Yaso-Magatsuhi no Kami. In another version (tenth alternate writing), it describes Izanagi creating Ōnaobi no Kami during his misogi, followed by the creation of Ōaya-Tsuhino-Kami (considered synonymous with Ōmagatsuhi no Kami).
