In the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kojiki|qq=}}, following the emergence of Yaso-Magatsuhi no Kami and Ōmagatsuhi no Kami, three deities were born: {{ill|Kamuna'obi|ja|神直毘神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamunaobi no Kami|qq=}} (神直毘神), {{ill|Ōnaobi no Kami|ja|大直毘神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōnaobi no Kami|qq=}} (大直毘神), and {{ill|Izanome|ja|伊豆能売|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izunome|qq=}}. In contrast, the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}}, in the fifth section, sixth alternate writing, states that Kamunaobi no Kami and Ōnaobi no Kami emerged after Yaso-Magatsuhi no Kami. In another version (tenth alternate writing), it describes Izanagi creating Ōnaobi no Kami during his misogi, followed by the creation of Ōaya-Tsuhino-Kami (considered synonymous with Ōmagatsuhi no Kami).
